subSection.paragraph:
Cyclotides are plant derived macrocyclic, bioactive mini-proteins with a characteristic head-to-tail cyclized backbone and a knotted arrangement of three cross-linked disulfide bonds. The first cyclotide, kalata B1 was discovered from the plant 

Oldenlandia affinis
(Rubiaceae)

by Dr. Lorents Gran in 1970. After more than 20 years of its discovery, the three-dimensional structural details were revealed by Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) studies (
Saether et al., 1995
). The decade of 1990s witnessed discovery of several more similar cyclized proteins from 
Violaceae
and 
Rubiaceae
families, which led to formal introduction of the name "cyclotides" to describe the family of these cyclized miniproteins consisting of 27–37 amino acids (
Craik et al., 1999
). Cyclotides have been found to be exceptionally stable proteins and resilient to heat, enzymes and chemical degradation (
Colgrave and Craik, 2004
). This stability is attributed to their cyclic cystine knot (CCK) structure formed by three disulphide linkages and cyclized backbone. Cyclotides play a role in defense of plants as revealed by their insecticidal activity (
Barbeta et al., 2008
; 
Jennings et al., 2001
; 
Pinto et al., 2012
; 
Simonsen et al., 2005
), anti-helminthic (
Colgrave et al., 2008
, 2009) and molluscicidal activities (
Colgrave et al., 2008
; 
Plan et al., 2008
). Besides their role in plants, cyclotides exhibit diverse range of bioactivities such as uterotonic (
Gran, 1973
), antibacterial (
Tam et al., 1999
; 
Ovesen et al., 2011
); anti-HIV (
Gustafson et al., 1994
), anticancer (
Lindholm et al., 2002
) and immuno-stimulants (
Nguyen et al., 2016
) which makes them important in pharmaceutical research.

The first indication of existence of acyclotides was the presence of putative cyclotide domain identified in maize plant of 
Poaceae
family (
Basse, 2005
). It was observed that gene 
Umi11
from maize plant, which got upregulated during pathogenic infection had a sequence similar to that of a cyclotide gene. This sequence lacked the terminal codon for aspartic acid (D)/asparagine (N) at the C-terminal end, crucial for cyclization, thus indicating the 
Umi 11
as a putative acyclotide gene. The first acyclotide to be isolated was violacin A (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

). Later, more such acyclotides have been isolated (
Table 1
) from all the angiosperm families in which cyclotides are also found (
Plan et al., 2007
; 
Trabi et al., 2009
; 
Mylne et al., 2012
; 
Nguyen et al., 2013
; 
Gilding et al., 2016
). These acyclotides were found to be structurally as stable as the cyclotides because of cystine knot structure but are susceptible to exoprotease activity because of lack of head to tail cyclization (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

). Although acyclotides lack peptide stability in terms of enzymatic degradation, they exhibit different bioactivities such as antimicrobial, cytotoxicity and hemolytic making them potential molecules for pharmaceutical and agricultural industries (
Gerlach et al., 2010
; 
Nguyen et al., 2013
). Of particular interest is the family 
Poaceae
(with crops like wheat, rice and maize which cater to the diet of world population) where only acyclotides have been discovered. As cyclotides are known to have potent pesticidal activity and role in plant defense pathways, it is worthwhile to explore these activities in all economically important 
Poaceae
members, thus opening opportunities for agriculture biotechnology and pest management. Consequently, harvesting large quantities of acyclotides for application in these areas is a major pre-requisite. Bulk production of acyclotides by overexpression in a heterologous host or chemical synthesis is less complex and more feasible compared to synthesis of cyclotides as the cyclization step is not required.

A year-wise literature search for articles on PubMed with keywords 'cyclotides' and 'acyclotides or linear cyclotides', indicates a much lower number of articles on acyclotides compared to those of cyclotides (
Fig. 1
). Although the importance of investigating acyclotides has been lately recognized, the number of publications are still low. To the best of our knowledge, there is no review article which provides comprehensive information on acyclotides. Keeping this in view and the emerging potential applications of acyclotides, this review presents an overview of their distribution, structure, biosynthesis, bioactivities and mechanism of action. Further, the potential pharmaceutical and agricultural applications of acyclotides along with their future perspectives have also been discussed.

Structurally, cyclotides can be categorized into three main subfamilies: Möbius, bracelet and trypsin inhibitors ( Craik et al., 1999 ; Hernandez et al., 2000 ). Most acyclotides also group into one of these three subfamilies. Of the listed 55 acyclotides, 24 are bracelet type , 18 Möbius type , 9 Möbius-like and four are from trypsin inhibitor (TI) subfamily ( Table 1 ). The Möbius type has a cis -amide bond with proline residue in loop 5 that causes a twist in the backbone; bracelet type has no twist in the backbone and trypsin inhibitors have sequences markedly different from both Möbius and bracelet types but have the same cystine knot. Besides these, there are acyclotides (panitides) which are categorized under Möbius-like subfamily because glycine replaces proline of loop 5 and brings about a twist in the protein structure ( Nguyen et al., 2013 ). The acyclotides have six loops and the same cystine linkages (CI–CIV, CII-CV) threaded by CIII-CVI (
Ireland et al., 2006b
), as in the cyclotides ( Saether et al., 1995 ). Loop analysis of all 55 cyclotides showed that loop 1 and loop 2 have consistently three and four amino acids respectively, except the trypsin inhibitors (MCoTI-3, MCoTI-5, MCoTI-6, Mobi 6) which have 6 amino acids in loop 1, and 5 amino acids in loop 2. Loop 4 has one amino acid only. Loops 3, 5 and 6 have a variable number and diverse amino acids. Even though the loop sizes vary in different acyclotides because of sequence length variation, the overall structure remain the same because of the three conserved disulfide linkages common to cyclotides and acyclotides.

Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) structures of only two acyclotides 
viz
. violacin A (PDB: 2FQA, subfamily: Möbius) and MCoTI-5 (PDB: 2LJS, subfamily: TI), are deposited in Protein Data Bank (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

; 
Mylne et al., 2012
). The amino acid sequences of these two acyclotides are very different but they have a similar overall topology because of the three conserved disulfide bonds forming the typical cystine knot structure. 

Ireland
et al. (2006b)

by NMR studies have revealed that structures of violacin A (acyclotide) and kalata B1(cyclotide) share the same topology. The three-dimensional structures of acyclotides overlaid on cyclotide show a good fit with only a slight distortion at the terminals (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

; 
Mylne et al., 2012
). Also, disulfide mapping of acyclotide, panitide L3 from 
Poaceae
showed that it has a similar cystine knot arrangement as that of cyclotides (
Nguyen et al., 2013
). Although the sequence homology between different acyclotides and cyclotides may be low (
Göransson and Craik, 2003
; 
He et al., 2011
; 
Nguyen et al., 2011a
), cystine spacing amongst them is similar resulting in the typical cystine knot structure.

Even though the acyclotides lack cyclic backbone, their stability or flexibility may be comparable to the cyclotides because, it is the three conserved disulfide linkages (forming cystine knot structure) that play a more important role in structural stability than cyclic topology (
Colgrave and Craik, 2004
; 
Heitz et al., 2008
). The secondary structure of the acyclotides MCoTI-5 and violacin A has a β-sheet motif. In violacin A, residues 21, 22, 25 and 26 form β-sheet while residues 17, 18 and 23, 24 
form two
β-turns (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

). In violacin A, loop 2 has been observed to contribute to the flexibility of the acyclotide (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

).

Studies describing biosynthesis of acyclotides per se are few (
Hellinger et al., 2015
; 
Nguyen et al., 2013
; 
Plan et al., 2007
; 
Serra et al., 2016
) compared to those of cyclotides (
Conlan et al., 2012
; 
Craik and Malik, 2013
; 
Gruber et al., 2007
; 
Harris et al., 2015
; 
Jackson et al., 2018
). However, as the structure and folds of acyclotides are similar to that of cyclotides, the initial processing pathway of acyclotides may be similar to the cyclotides. The cyclotides are known to be synthesized by a multistep process which starts with transcription, ribosomal translation of precursor proteins, transport to ER, disulphide folding, cleavage and finally cyclization (
Craik and Malik, 2013
). The natural processing of cyclotides in plants involves oxidization of disulphide bonds in the precursor protein within the ER followed by cleavage and cyclization of cyclotide domain in the vacuole, further along the secretory pathway (
Gruber et al., 2007
; 
Jennings et al., 2001
). Presence of the processing enzyme (asparaginyl endopeptidase, AEP), which recognizes the conserved C-terminal D/N residue in the vacuolar compartment, gives evidence of cyclization in the vacuole (
Conlan et al., 2011
). The enzyme AEP functions for both cleavage of the precursor protein (propeptide) and cyclization at the C-terminal residue D or N (
Harris et al., 2015
; 
Saska et al., 2007
).

In case of acyclotides, they exist as acyclic analogues of cyclotides (eg kalata B9, kalata B10; 
Plan et al., 2007
), or without any cyclic forms (eg panitides; 
Nguyen et al., 2013
) (see 
Table 1
). The biosynthesis of acyclotides without the cyclic forms such as panitides (
Nguyen et al., 2013
), acyclic chassatides (
Nguyen et al., 2012
), hedyotide B2 (
Nguyen et al., 2011a
), violacin A (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

), Phyb M (
Poth et al., 2012
) is genetically pre-determined as shown by the presence of premature stop codon or a mutation of D/N codon at the C-terminal end of acyclotide domain. The stop codon truncates the propeptide before the translation of D/N resulting in lack of cyclization. Further, in the acyclotide, hedyotide B2, it was observed that the N-terminal end of the precursor protein had a glycine residue, which was absent in mature protein. This might be either due to direct cleavage or proteolysis of the glycine residue by aminopeptidases (found in abundance in plant vacuoles) due to lack of protection in the acyclotide, unlike that in a cyclized protein (
Nguyen et al., 2011a
). It is noteworthy that even though, all acyclic analogues of cyclotides have either D or N at C-terminal of the peptide chain, they still remain acyclic (
Hellinger et al., 2015
) and 
form disulfide
linkages to 
form the
characteristic cystine knot motif. These acyclic analogues maybe the premature cyclotides which would eventually cyclize or are acyclized forms generated by cleavage of the N-terminal and C-terminal bond by anhydrides or succinimides (
Plan et al., 2007
). In this regard, it remains to be investigated (i) whether the acyclotides with D/N at C-terminal end remain acyclic throughout the life cycle of plant or are converted to cyclic forms under certain biotic/ abiotic stress; (ii) why some acyclotides are observed as acyclic analogues of certain cyclotides only (24 acyclic analogues of 24 cyclotides, see 
Table 1
) and not universally.

Recently, 
Nguyen et al. (2013)
postulated that in panitides (acyclotides of 

P. laxum

), the ER signal sequence directs the precursor protein to ER for folding. However, the role of NTPP and NTR domain in biosynthesis of acyclotides is still not clearly understood (
Mylne et al., 2012
). On the other hand, in cyclotides, the presence of only single NTPP domain even with multiple cyclotide domains suggests its negligible role in folding of the proteins (
Gunasekera et al., 2006
). However, 
Conlan et al. (2011)
by their experiments using GFP in 

Nicotiana benthamiana

established that NTPP and NTR sequences help to lead the proteins to vacuole where cleavage of the mature cyclotide domain takes place. Until 2016, it was understood that in most cases, a mature cyclotide domain encodes for either a cyclotide or an acyclotide, but not both. This was because the cyclization process is very efficient due to which the presence of acyclotides is very rare. The acyclotides that are present throughout are normally encoded by genes lacking codon for critical D/N residue (
Gilding et al., 2016
; 

Ireland
et al., 2006b

; 
Mylne et al., 2010
; 
Nguyen et al., 2016
). Lately, 
Serra et al. (2016)
working on diversity of cliotides (i.e cyclotides and acyclotides from 

Clitoria ternatea

) found that a single cliotide gene can produce up to seven different acyclic and cyclic proteins. This is attributed to inefficient or ‘fuzzy’ bio-processing of precursor proteins by the cyclization enzyme which leads to production of both cyclotides and acyclotides from same domain.

The cyclotides have a natural role as defense molecules in plants (
Jennings et al., 2001
). They also possess a wide range of bioactivities such as anti-HIV, antimicrobial, anti-cancer, uterotonic, antihelminthic, insecticidal and hemolytic activity (
Colgrave et al., 2008
; 
Gerlach et al., 2010
; 
Gran, 1973
; 
Gustafson et al., 1994
; 
Jennings et al., 2001
; 
Tam et al., 1999
; 
Wang et al., 2009
). In case of acyclotides, less than 50% of the discovered acyclotides have been screened for these bioactivities. Earlier experiments on linearized versions of kalata B1 showed loss of all activities upon linearization (
Daly and Craik, 2000
). Experimentally linearized cyclotides (acyclic permutants) obtained by breaking any individual peptide bond of a cyclotide, did not show its original bioactivities such as hemolytic (
Barry et al., 2003
) and anti-HIV activities (
Daly et al., 2004
). Linearized homologs of cyclotide MCoTI-II from 
Cucurbitaceae
(oMCoTI-II, oMCoTI-IIA10, oMCoTI-IIA13, oMCoTI-IIA14, oMCoTI-IIR10, oMCoTI-IIR13, oMCoTI-IIR14) showed decreased trypsin inhibiting activity compared to the cyclized forms (
Avrutina et al., 2005
). However, alanine scan of kalata B1 (where individual amino acid residues were mutated without linearizing the cyclotide) showed that more than cyclic backbone, the individual residues which alter the surface hydrophobicity of the protein are responsible for the potency of the bioactivity (
Simonsen et al., 2008
). Here it may be pointed out that unlike the acyclotides, the cyclic backbone of cyclotides, can resist thermal and enzymatic degradation in an exopeptidase environment, and therefore contribute to peptide stability and the bioactivites shown by the cyclotides (
Colgrave and Craik, 2004
). Later, 
Nguyen et al. (2012)
showed acyclotides from 

Chassalia chartacea

(chassatides) to have potent antimicrobial, cytotoxic, and haemolytic activities, indicating that cyclic backbone may not be essential for the bioactivity.

The naturally occurring acyclotides which exist in the plant only in acyclic forms (
Gerlach et al., 2010
; 
Nguyen et al., 2012
) show antimicrobial, cytotoxic and/or hemolytic activity (see 
Table 1
). Thus, with caution, it may be indicated that genetically predetermined, naturally occurring acyclotides which do not coexist with their cyclic forms, have demonstrated the assessed bioactivities. On the other hand, cyclotides which are experimentally made acyclic/linearized lose the activity (
Barry et al., 2003
; 
Daly et al., 2004
). The acyclotides which coexist (with their respective cyclotides) in a plant have not been screened for any bioactivities (
Table 1
).

Bioactivities such as insecticidal, molluscicidal, anti-helminthic, have not yet been assayed for acyclotides. Antimicrobial activity has been reported in four of the discovered acyclotides, in panitide L2 (
Nguyen et al., 2013
) and chassatides C7, C8 and C11 (
Nguyen et al., 2012
). Their level of activity varied between 2.5 μM and 8.5 μM MIC (Minimum Inhibitory Concentration), panitide L2 being the most potent. The three acyclic chassatides (C7, C8, C11) showed stronger activity compared to the cyclic chassatides and the prototype cyclotide kalata B1 (
Nguyen et al., 2012
). The acyclotide, hedyotide B2 (from 

Hedyotis biflora

, 
Rubiaceae
), was found to be inactive against both gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria (
Nguyen et al., 2011a
). None of the acyclotides showing antimicrobial activity were active against gram-positive bacteria. The thick peptidoglycan layer in gram-positive bacteria might hinder the electrostatic interaction required for the antimicrobial activity of the acyclotides (
Nguyen et al., 2013
, 
2012
).

Cytotoxicity has been shown in twelve acyclotides (panitides L1-L8, Psyle C, chassatide C7, C8, C11) exhibiting varying degree of cytotoxic activity against cancer cells. However, the most potent ones showing half maximal inhibitory concentration (IC 
50
) <10 μM are, three chassatides (C7, C8, C11), five panitides (pL1, pL2, pL5, pL6, pL7) and Psyle C (
Gerlach et al., 2010
; 
Nguyen et al., 2013
, 
2012
). Psyle C has been found to be a highly effective chemo-sensitizing agent against drug-resistant cancer cells. It causes selective membrane disruption and pore formation in cancer cells allowing the accumulation of cancer drug inside the resistant cells (
Gerlach et al., 2010
). According to 
Herrmann et al. (2006)
, in case of the cyclotide, cycloviolacin O2, cytotoxic activity depends on the surface exposed amino acid residues and the intact cystine knot structure rather than the sequence between the six conserved cysteine residues. Further, the glutamic acid residue in loop 1, is crucial in maintaining the cytotoxic activity of the cyclotide. For acyclotides like chassastide C11 also, the surface exposed hydrophobic residues play a role in cytotoxicity and its potency is comparable to cyclic chassatides (
Nguyen et al., 2012
).

Three acyclotides (chassatide C7, C8 and C11) have also been reported to show strong potent hemolytic activity against human red blood cells (
Nguyen et al., 2012
). The fewer numbers of acyclotides showing hemolytic activity, might be due to only two investigations (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

; 
Nguyen et al., 2012
). In violacin A, the weak hemolytic activity observed was attributed to its acyclic backbone, as other cyclotides with cyclic backbone from 
Violaceae
showed strong hemolytic activity (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

). Further, experimental linearization of cyclic backbone of cyclotides have also resulted in loss of hemolytic activity (
Daly and Craik, 2000
; 
Barry et al., 2003
). However, on the contrary, acyclic chassatides showed potent hemolytic activity of similar degree to that of cyclic chassatides (
Nguyen et al., 2012
), indicating that lack of cyclic backbone may not be the reason for absence of hemolytic activity.

There are fewer studies elucidating the mechanism of action of acyclotides compared to those of cyclotides. In cyclotides, their bioactivities are strongly correlated to their membrane binding ability (
Wang et al., 2012
). They directly interact with the phosphatidylethanolamine (PE) of lipid membranes via hydrophobic interactions (
Henriques et al., 2012
). This interaction is followed by self-polymerization and pore formation in the membrane. The activity of cyclotides is a result of combined interaction of its structure, net charge and hydrophobicity with the target membrane leading to altered membrane permeability (
Henriques et al., 2012
; 
Huang et al., 2009
; 
Kamimori et al., 2005
; 
Wang et al., 2009
). It is reasonable to suggest that the mechanism of action of acyclotides could also be the same as they have the same structural topology as the cyclotides. Further, there are evidences to indicate that hydrophobicity of the interacting surface and net charge of acyclotides also play a role in their bioactivity. This has been demonstrated in the following studies: (i) the naturally occurring acyclotide, violacin A has reduced hemolytic activity compared to the prototype cyclotide, kalata B1 (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

). However, a complete loss of hemolytic activity was observed in the acyclic permutants of kalata B1 (
Daly and Craik, 2000
). It was postulated that the high degree of hydrophobicity leads to high hemolytic activity and as violacin A is more hydrophilic than kalata B1, it has reduced activity. Thus the reduced activity of violacin A might not be due to lack of cyclized backbone but because of its reduced hydrophobicity (

Ireland
et al., 2006b

). (ii) The acyclotides (chassatides C7, C8 and C11), show more hemolytic activity due to their intact hydrophobic patch (
Nguyen et al., 2012
). Their higher hydrophobicity ratio (> 50%) also correlates with high cytotoxicity (
Nguyen et al., 2012
). (iii) Evidence of the impact of hydrophobicity on membranolytic activity is provided by oxidation of methionine residue of acyclic chassatide, which leads to increase of hydrophilicity and consequently loss of antimicrobial, cytotoxic and hemolytic activities (
Nguyen et al., 2012
). (iv) Electrostatic interaction between the bacterial membrane and acyclotides also play a major role in antimicrobial activity. The acyclotides and cyclotides with high net positive charge are found to be effective against microbes. In 
Poaceae
, the panitide L2 with +2 charge shows antimicrobial effect, while the rest of the panitides with neutral or +1 charge are inactive against the microbes (
Nguyen et al., 2013
). Similarly, neutral or negatively charged chassatides are non-antimicrobial whereas the positively charged acyclotides (chassatides C7, C8) show moderate antimicrobial activity (
Nguyen et al., 2012
).

Acyclotides do not have a cyclic backbone, but share similar overall structure and stability of the cyclotides. Both cyclotides and acyclotides are found in five dicot families. However, until now only acyclotides have been isolated from a monocot family (
Poaceae
). The genetically pre-determined acyclotides (eg violacin A, panitides, psyle C and acyclic chassatides) lack the crucial D/N residue at the C-terminal end, which is required for cyclization. These acyclotides show diverse bioactivities resulting from its hydrophobicity and electrostatic interactions with target biological membranes. Their comparable bioactivities with prototype cyclotide kalata B1, indicate that although cyclization provides peptide stability, the cyclic backbone may not be essential for biological activities. This opens up a range of potential agricultural and pharmaceutical applications. Further, the omission of cyclization step during heterologous expression or transgenic production adds to the feasibility of its applications.
